bug.short_desc: Behavior of DropTargetEvent on TreeViewer changed from 3.1.2 to 3.2

long_desc.thetext: I have a DropTargetListener associated with my TreeViewer and when the DropTargetListener receives a DropTargetEvent the event.item turns out to be the first child of the dropped on tree item. Previousliy in 3.1.2 the behavior was correct. The DropTargetEvent event.item is actually the TreeItem which the cursor was released upon.

Created an attachment (id=47327) a modified snippet91 that prints event.item
Attached is a modified http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/index.cgi/%7Echeckout%7E/org.eclipse.swt.snippets/src/org/eclipse/swt/snippets/Snippet91.java which prints event.item for all DropTargetListener methods, and it seems to work for me. Does it work for you (ie.- it prints the correct item)? And if so, can you make a similar snippet that shows a case where the wrong item is printed?

Taking a hint from bug 152766 (likely a duplicate of this report) I do see an off-by-1 regression in the drawing of the focus dots on currently-hovered item iff the header is visible. In such a case, if the pointer is over item x then item x-1 has the focus dots, and dropping here sets the event's item to item x. This is incorrect if the focus-dotted item is the intended drop target.
*** Bug 152766 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

To update, it has been determined that the fix for bug 142880 fixed the wrong event.item problem, but introduced the off-by-one problem described in comment 2.
I'm going to reopen bug 142880 since introducing a new regression in the process of fixing an old one isn't a good thing. Marking this report as a duplicate since the original problem described here was fixed by the original fix for bug 142880.

bug.short_desc: [Dialogs] Control Dialogs ButtonBar using Bit-Mask

long_desc.thetext:
At the moment if you want a Dialog having only a Ok or Cancle-Button one needs to overwrite createButtonsForButtonBar. When one could set a mask like e.g. setButtonBarMask(IDialogConstants.OK_MASK|IDialogConstants.CANCLE_MASK) this would be much more generic.

The API (as well as the constant values) have been defined for 5+ years, so there are literally thousands of dialogs programmed to this behavior. We would need a compelling reason to introduce an alternative way of defining a button bar. We really aren't at a stage in the project to revisit the convenience of an API, but if there is really a problem here with the current design (ie, you can't achieve what you need to achieve), then we definitely want to understand it.
Another point: bitmasking the buttons doesn't give the app any chance to affect the order.

You probably know this, but just in case.... For simple message dialogs, you can just specify the array of strings for the buttons, or use the static methods that create canned button configurations. See class MessageDialog and its subclasses.

bug.short_desc: API: IJavaProject.setRawClasspath with validate edit context

long_desc.thetext:
3.2
When IJavaProject.setRawClasspath modifies the .classpath file it calls validateEdit before the modification. As it has no context it passes 'null' as context.
Unfortunatly validateEdit is not very useful to the user without context. The user expects to be prompted when a file is checked-out, but won't if context is null. (see for example bug 141451). IMO it should be avoided to call validateEdit with null.
I see no other solution than adding new API on setRawClasspath that also takes a context. I agree that this looks ugly. The alternative is that jdt.ui changes it's calls to setRawClasspath to first call validateEdit on .classpath. In theory, jdt.ui doesn't know that the file is called .classpath. We have ~20 references to setRawClasspath so we would introduce a utility that replaces setRawClasspath and adds an additional validate edit first.
API suggestion:
IStatus setRawClasspath(IClasspathEntry[] entries, IPath outputLocation, Object validateEditContext, IProgressMonitor monitor)

bug.short_desc: Unable to use Text controls as "labels with copy" on Tabs in Windows XP

long_desc.thetext:
This is related to a fix to the following bug to allow gradient tabs on suitably themed Windows XP machines (https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=24538).
Often a Text control is used when displaying values where you want the value to be able to be copy/pasted (i.e. the current path of a file, that sort of thing). However, there is no way to get a Text control on a tab control to allow the gradient fill though - it is aways displayed as a gray rectangle.
The following pattern is commonly used:-
Text valueText = new Text(composite, SWT.READ_ONLY); valueText.setBackground( valueText .getDisplay() .getSystemColor(SWT.COLOR_WIDGET_BACKGROUND));
The reason the .setBackground is required is that on GTK, a read-only text box would have a plain white background, whereas until this bug mentioned above was fixed you always wanted the background of the Text control to be that of the widget it was on so that it looked just like a Label (only with the ability to select and copy text from it)
The use of text controls as labels is a fairly well established technique used in many places in existing projects.
org.eclipse.ui.internal.ide.dialogs.ResourceInfoPage org.eclipse.jface.dialogs.InputDialog org.eclipse.ui.texteditor.MessageRegion org.eclipse.ui.internal.dialogs.ErrorPreferencePage
All have examples of this usage. Additionally the technique is used in the Windows Operating System (right click on a file in Explorer, select Properties)
It would be nice to have a way to do this in SWT. The work-arounds are to
1) explicitly set the background of the Tab control to SWT.COLOR_WIDGET_BACKGROUND - thereby unfixing bug 24538 but giving you an inconsistent UI experience
2) Create a context menu on a label that has a "Copy" option. This is not a total workaround because the text is not selectable so you would have to copy the entire contents of the label.
Thanks.
Martin.

bug.short_desc: Nested GridLayout allows child to be larger than parent

long_desc.thetext:
My understanding of GridLayout parameters is that the grabExcessHorizontalSpace parameter in GridData allows a child to grab excess space within it's parent, but not grab extra space from outside its parent.
I will attach example code which shows the behavior in the context of a JFace TitleAreaDialog. The example is a boiled-down version of a problem we encountered in an RCP/plugin project.
Run the example (you will need core.runtime, jface and swt), press the "push me" and observe the resulting dialog. You can see that inner panel (yellow background) is larger than the outer panel (grey background, bordered by red). Pushing the "show sizes" button will print the width of the inner and outer panels to system out. If you then comment out line 104 and enable line 106 (see comments in the code) and re-run, you will see the fields sized correctly. The only difference is the value of the grabExcessHorizontalSpace parameter in the GridData constructor.
Created an attachment (id=47321) Example of nested grid layout problem

The comments are correct. The problem is that when the InnerPanel is allowed to be it's preferred size, it causes the parent container (OuterPanel) to become larger than it's container and causes other controls within the OuterPanel to grow as well. According to the javadocs for GridData.grabExcessHorizontalSpace : "If there is not enough horizontal space available in the parent, the cell will shrink until it reaches its minimum width as specified by GridData.minimumWidth." The default minimum width (0) is used. So, if my understanding of the javadocs is correct, no setting of the grabExcessHorizontalSpace parameter should allow children in a container with a GridLayout to be larger than the parent. Is this incorrect?
I will attach a screenshot. The grey background in the screenshot is the OuterPanel and the yellow background is the InnerPanel. You can see that the InnerPanel and other controls in the OuterPanel become larger than the parent container. Or maybe the OuterPanel grows larger than _its_ parent (red background) -- but that has a FillLayout and the javadocs for FillLayout indicate that it does not allow its children to be larger than the container, either. I encourage you to find somebody who can run the code so you can see it in action.

1) Explain why you believe this is a stop-ship defect. How does the defect manifest itself, and how will users of TPTP / consuming products be affected if the defect is not fixed?
I believe this is a stop-ship defect because it is a highly visbile regression that can have very adverse effects on a TPTP consuming product. A particular consuming product produces test logs with no verdicts by default (unless settings are adjusted to include additional data in the test log.) There are several ways in which this becomes problematic for the consuming product (and for TPTP as well). No

Paul Slauenwhite

7) What is the risk associated with this fix?
Nearly zero risk. The fix simply adds an if statement to verify that an object is not null before the object is dereferenced. Without this fix, a NullPointerException will be thrown, which will cascade up the call stack until caught, thus circumventing other important functionality.

- Unified EL support means that we need to overhaul the current variable/property resolver framework. - Support for FunctionMapper's means that we must fix problems parsing EL functions and support their linking where possible to a corresponding Java static method. - Implicit objects now truly implicit: no longer able to override in the variable resolver. - Unfound loadBundles now throw exceptions: validation here increases in importance. - Resource bundles can now be loaded through the faces-config file (new variable resolver) without a loadBundle tag. - Managed beans now support Java 5 annotations. - <c:forEach> JSTL tag can interoperate with JSF tags. - Specific algorithm for generating tag ids. This may be useful in implementing bi-directional linking of components to source tags because we can be guaranteed that our ids wont be changed. - There are now standard converter messages that can be resolved by id. - Faces config file now schema instead of DTD based.

Also changes to standard component properties that may require support:
h:column: Add headerClass and footerClass attributes. Possible new meta-data required.
All UIInput tags: Add optional label attribute that adds a information about a component. May need to process in order to perform design time WYSIWYG text substitutions.
h:outputLink and h:commandLink: Add disabled property. New meta-data required.
f:verbatim: Add rendered attribute to control rendering. New meta-data
f:setPropertyActionListener: New tag. New analysis required.
f:view: Add renderKitId attribute. New meta-data.
Triaged for WTP 2.0. Please close this bug if the features listed here are already being tracked in the wiki page:http://wiki.eclipse.org/index.php/Support_for_JavaServer_Faces_1.2_%28Java_5_EE%29

bug.short_desc: Importing a datapool does nothing when clicking on Finish

long_desc.thetext:
Steps to Reproduce Problem... When importing a datapool without creating as new... 1. Click on File -> Import
Inside the Import dialog window: 2. Select datapool under Test folder, then click on Next 3. Browse... to a CSV file and click Open 4. Click on Finish.
Nothing happens.
Please investigate for 4.2.1

I misunderstood this defect based on its description -- importing datapools still works properly. The defect described here is that the finish button is enabled prematurely, and clicking on it before completing the import steps does nothing. The fix is to simply disbale the finish button until all necessary input has been provided by the user.
Targeting to 4.3

Notice the difference between the directory naming and the reported version in that one case. I've not looked at any others.
Should the <import feature="org.uddi4j.feature" version="2.0.3"/> be using match="equivalent" or match="somethingelse" since most of the time what you really mean is a range from the explicit oldest version upto the maximum version that maintains a API and/or binary compatability contract with that version for that feature/plugin.
Some random thoughts:
Is there a headless plugin integrity check that can be run like a test case against an installation to look check:
* That all features/plugins are resolved.
* That can pretend to be a future version of WTP like 1.5.9999 (as far forward as you are claiming binary level compatatiblity maybe this is into 2.0.x) and confirm that all features/plugins still resolve, basically some such test that can confirm everything still works in the future upto your binary compatability contact.
* Can check for naming problems, for example: * Check the feature/plugin directory name matches the internal name. (in the features.xml/plugin.xml descirptors), like the "org.eclipse.wst" part. * Check the feature/plugin version part of the directory matches the internal name (in the features.xml/plugin.xml descirptors), like the "1.5.0.v200601010101_whatever" part.
Let the computer take the strain of checking a release is ready and spotting problems.

Inside WTP it looks like:
* plugin version numbers follow API Interface versioning. Because plugins/org.eclipse.wst_1.0.1.v200605040144.jar exists in WTP 1.5. Where as seeing 1.5 is expected (and better understood with clarity by an on looker).
* feature version numbers follow product version numbers. Because features/org.eclipse.wst_1.5.0.v200606092300-U4T922yjOWsGK5Y exists in WTP 1.5.
But comparing this arrangement with other feature/plugins I get the impression most other things bump up the plugin version number to keep inline with their product release.
Those that DO bump inline:
Platform, EMF (most of but ), XSD, JEM, GEF, VE, CDT, BIRT.
EMF looks like it bumped but parts didn't: org.eclipse.emf.codegen.ui, org.eclipse.emf.ecore.change.edit, org.eclipse.emf.commonj.sdom, org.eclipse.emf.ecore.sdo.edit, org.eclipse.emf.ecore.sdo.editor parts didn't, the rest did into 2.2. from 2.1).
Those that DO NOT:
WTP, DataTools.

"most other things bump up the plugin version number to keep inline with their product release" this is actually a temporary thing ... since the "new rules" just started with the Callisto release ... its expected this will not be the general case. Features can vary a great deal from product to product (adopter to adopter), and even install to install ... with no widespread correspondence to plugin versions ... but, plugins should follow the versioning rules to be meaningful in terms of degree of change, api compatibility, etc.
I'll need to read your actual "config" errors to see if I can understand when you are seeing this ... what is the context? What do you start with? Which update site?

DIST_ECLIPSE="eclipse-SDK-3.2-linux-gtk-x86_64.tar.gz" DIST_EMFSDOXSD="emf-sdo-xsd-SDK-2.2.0.zip" DIST_GEF="GEF-SDK-3.2.zip" DIST_JEM="JEM-SDK-1.2.zip" DIST_VE="VE-SDK-1.2.zip" DIST_BIRT="birt-report-framework-sdk-2_1_0.zip" DIST_CDT="org.eclipse.cdt.sdk-3.1.0-linux.x86_64.tar.gz" DIST_WTP="wtp-sdk-M-1.5.1-200607272136.zip"

Hence my integrity checking suggestions to make sure a build is self-consitant. But I think my <plugin ...> quote in the opening comment is a redherring, as I had overlooked the <feature ...> descriptor at the top of the file and it wasn't understood by me that a feature can be at a lower version level than the plugin (this point still mistifies me now). I am still thinking in terms of bump and ripple. A plugin gets incremented when the source code changes, a feature gets incemented when anything inside it changes and is pulled upwards to keep inline with product releases.

bug.short_desc: Run On Server will not start server if startBeforePublish is false

long_desc.thetext:
If a web app is published to a server (synchronized) that does not support startBeforePublish, and then the server is stopped, RunOnServerAction will not start the server.
In the RunOnServerAction the startServerJob is chained to the publishServerJob for a stopped server. However if the server does not support startBeforePublish then PublishServerJob.shouldRun() will return false, which perks up to the job having a state of CANCEL. As a result any subsequent jobs in the chain are not run, and the server is not started.
Perhaps the RunOnServerAction can use another branch if the server is stopped+synchronized and only call the startServerJob.
I have a patch for this problem, but as it turns out there is one scenario that still fails. I need to review the code with Tim to see if this is a problem in our code or a problem from the adapter.

We determined the problem can be resolved by moving the shouldPublish() on the Task.
Tim, over to you for checking of the code.
Fix checked into HEAD.
Fix released to 1.5 and 2.0 streams.
Closing.

bug.short_desc: [performance] BP2201 is reading the WSDL document again for each <port> element defined in the WSDL file

long_desc.thetext:
Build: WTP 1.5.1 0803
The purpose of BP2201 is to make sure the XML declaration of the WSDL document is either UTF-8 or UTF-16. Since this information is not captured in the WSDL model, the current implementation will go off to the hard disk and read the WSDL document again to determine if the XML declaration is valid. The current implemenation does this for each <definition> element that it encounters. There are couple improvements that we can make:
1. Instead of reading from disk, get the XML declaration from else where 2. For each WSDL document, regardless of how many <definition> elements are in there, process the XML declaration once
I meant the <port> element, not the <definition> element.

Created an attachment (id=47366) patch for wst.wsi (BP2201)
Here's one way to address concern #2..... Please review and determine if it is something we can commit. Thanks.

Re: 1. Instead of reading from disk, get the XML declaration from else where
We can cache the DOM Element represenation of the WSDL document in org.eclipse.wst.wsi.internal.core.wsdl.WSDLDocument, and make it available thru a getter method. By doing so, BP2201 can use this DOM Element later to validate the XML declaration encoding.

bug.short_desc: Would like to reduce data down-/upload during native build process

long_desc.thetext:
In talking over Eclipse TPTP's build process with some Intel build engineers, I again was faced with the enormity of the quantity of data we download and then upload that is really not absolutely necessary.
I'd like to propose that perhaps our "2-stage" build become a "3-stage" one, whereby when we finish with our Intel architecture native builds, we upload our specific native packages, but all the resultant "all_platforms" packaging then takes place upstream. Right now I think we're doing an additional 170Meg for tptpdc, 130 for agntctrl, with lesser amounts (that still add up) for cbe and JVMTI all_platforms, not to mention the all_platforms.sdk packages as well.
Randy, can you explain what "all the resultant all_platforms packaging then takes place upstream" mean? Do you mean updating the all-platform zip files on the eclipse download server?

Right, what I'm saying is that all the {tptpdc|agntctrl|cbe|probekit|javaprofiler}.all_platform[.sdk] files are just rolled up versions of bigger trees containing exact replicas of what is in the smaller trees containing the individual packages. Do we really need to download that 150+MB of data and subsequently upload 350-400MB of data when that half-gig+ of data is redundant? Subsequent to my builds, an "all_platforms packing effort" could build those all_platforms files.

Randy, Why do you call the "all_platforms packing effort" the 3rd step? Are you just changing the way the all platform zip files are packaged (in the 2nd step)? I suppose the build is complete only after the all-platform zip files are all updated.

I call it the third step just as a proposal; that's the nature of the enhancement request. We have two steps now... one up at IBM Toronto (TPTP runtime build and some native), and one over here at Intel Oregon (remaining Intel architecture native builds)... I propose to add a third step back there whose sole purpose is to zip up those all_platforms files... but zip them up back at IBM Toronto to avoid submitting the same bits multiple times. I'd remove the creation and uploading of all_platforms zip files from *my* current build process, and you'd finish it there instead.

Randy, now I understand your proposal. (I didn't understand the 3rd step was to be done by me at the beginning.) Adding an extra step and hand shake between us may complicate the build, and make it more difficult to complete one build. I have a counter proposal. If the bottleneck is in transferring the big all-platform files, can you do the updating of the all-platform zip files on the eclipse download site? That is, you only download what's required to do your builds (the nativecode.zip) and create the AC and CBE packages for platforms that you are responsible for. Upload the individual platform zip files to eclipse, and you update the all-platforms zip files directly on eclispe download server. You can keep the script in your home directory. The script should be fairly straightforward. Do you like this approach?

Wow... I hadn't thought of that... I guess I just saw that box as a repository... I presume it's not unreasonable to do unzip/zips there script driven. Sounds like a good counter-proposal... so I guess just assign it to me then. Thanks for the suggestion!

Kiryl, another low priority, though even nicer to have than the last. Note it's an "enhancement request". Comment #5 below is most apropos... the best solution, probably, keeps the 2-stage approach. In this case, you wouldn't download BIG packages, overlay with our stuff, and upload. Instead, you'd build and upload the minimal necessary, and then run scripts at the upload site to repackage there. This will cut the bandwidth for the builds substantially!

Some work has been done in the context of bug #178141.
Downstream build creates six agntctrl.* packages (for each supported platform), upload them to dev.eclipse.org. And then do remotely the following things: 1) updates them with some plug-ins taken from TPTP zip files 2) assemble tptpdc.all_platforms and agntctrl.all_platforms packages
It save us from downloading big TPTP zip files to downstream build host and upload big *.all_platforms files.

Some more optimizations may be done. Mainly to prepare remained "all" packages remotely.
To be reviewed on completion of bug 182085.

bug.short_desc: [import/export] EAR Import performance degradation

long_desc.thetext:
I have an EAR file that takes a VERY long time to import into a IBM product building on top of Eclipse WTP 1.0.2. I have also tried this using a 1.5 build as well and I receive the same very slow import performance - it takes at least 30 minutes or more to import the EAR. I have taken a few different javacores while WTP was running and I will attach them to this bugzilla. It looks like the following may be the culprit:
org/eclipse/jst/j2ee/commonarchivecore/internal/impl/ArchiveImpl.save
I cannot provide the EAR file due to confidentiality reasons but if there is any additional information I can provide then please let me know.
Created an attachment (id=47370) javacore*.txt files while trying to import an EAR file
Please email me the failing EAR.
This is a big problem; I received the EAR from troy and performance is very bad.

Created an attachment (id=48010) Patch
The problem was a linear search done on nested archives for importing .class files without source when the import stream was requested. This was leading to a N squared running time for the number of .class files without source. The fix is to identify the .class files up front and then import them later (rather than importing them upfront) using the FileIterator supplied by the base SaveStrategy code. This iterator keeps track of the index in the nested archive so no searching is done when requesting the io stream. Some other changes were necessary in order to correctly place the imported class files in the project structure; the paths needed to be project relative rather than component relative.

Created an attachment (id=48055) A better patch
This patch contains a few additinal changes in the J2EEComponentSaveStrategy so the imported classes are not gathered up first, but rather are determined during the shouldSave(File) method. This improves performace by not iterating over the file list, or needing to put/retrieve entries from the collection.

Approved
